#!/usr/bin/env julia

#=

This challenge is to produce the shortest code for the constant π^(1/π). Your code must output the first n consecutive digits of π^(1/π), where n is given in the input. Alternatively, your program may accept no input, and output digits indefinitely

This is code golf, so the shortest submission (in bytes) wins except that it must output the 1000 digits for n=1000 in less than 10 seconds on a reasonable PC.

You may not use a built-in for π, the gamma function or any trigonometic functions.

If the input is n=1000 then the output should be:

1.
Note the 1000 decimal places includes the first 1.

Output format

Your code can output in any format you wish.

This related question tackles a simpler variant but with the same restrictions.

Notes

If it's helpful, you can assume π1/π is irrational and in fact you can even assume it is a Normal number.

=#

function pipower(n)
	setprecision(BigFloat, n*1000)
	x = BigFloat(4) * atan(BigFloat(1))
	r = x ^ (1/x)
	return first(string(r), n+1)
end

println(pipower(1000))
